<br>
  “Lunge, parry, thrust, kick, parry, lunge, parry, kick, thrust, parry.”<br>
<br>
  The drill sergeant’s voice rang out, loudly, clearly, and exactly in time with his rough barking was the clang of metal on metal.  The drill sergeant wheeled around just in time to see a young dwarf hit the ground.<br>
<br>
  “Up maggot!” The voice boomed over the chuckles.  The dwarf was smaller and younger than the rest, starting the school early because he showed promise.  Quickly advanced, he was now in a room full of much older recruits, and the physical tests were getting more and more vigorous.  He wondered how much his young body could take; he definitely wasn’t as strong as the others.  In sparring he got away with it due to his quickness, but in drills that was no help to him.  Sighing softly he got back up and resumed the battle position.  <br>
<br>
  The sergeant smiled softly under his helm, ‘this one certainly shows much promise, and determination.  He will go on to do great things.  It’s too bad that my job requires me to try and break him.’<br>
<br>
  Wheeling around again, the sergeant hollered, “Kordaaf, to the front.”  The young dwarf quickly hurried to the front of the training room.  “Prepare yourself.”  They touched weapons as the sergeant’s assistant began to call out the orders.  The young dwarf struggled against the veteran’s power, but he stood his ground.  Blood, sweat, tears, pain; nothing could quell his desire for greatness.<br>
<br>
  “Lunge, kick, parry, thrust, lunge, lunge, parry, kick, parry.”<br>
